      "fix_scope": "single_edit",
      "root_cause_cluster": "inconsistent_boundary_error_model"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "http_error_boundary_double_write",
      "summary": "Upload error handler writes a response, returns error, then caller emits a second error response",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/importer/importer.go",
        "goseg/importer/importer_test.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`failUploadRequest` calls `sendUploadResponse` before returning, then returns publish/IO errors via `sendErr` and `publishErr`",
        "`HTTPUploadHandler` invokes `failUploadRequest` and, on error, logs and calls `http.Error`, which attempts to write a second status/body after one may already be committed",
        "The code path is reachable from validation, chunk parsing, and pipeline failure handling in the same function",
        "Tests validate that `failUploadRequest` returns publish errors but do not assert response integrity for the caller-level override path"
      ],
      "suggestion": "Split transport and side-channel failures: make `failUploadRequest` return a typed result (e.g., `responseWritten bool` + `err`) or a structured `error` channel so callers either write their own HTTP response once or explicitly skip secondary `http.Error` when a response was already sent.",
